  "prompt": "How is hashCode in Java implemented and when should I override it?",
  "response": "**Implementation of `hashCode` in Java**\n\nThe `hashCode` method in Java is implemented in the `Object` class, which is the superclass of all Java objects. The implementation is as follows:\n\n```java\npublic native int hashCode();\n```\n\nThe `native` keyword indicates that the implementation is provided by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and is not written in Java. The JVM uses a unique identifier for each object, which is used to generate the hash code.\n\n**When to Override `hashCode`**\n\nYou should override `hashCode` when you override `equals`. This is because `equals` and `hashCode` are closely related, and the contract between them requires that:\n\n* If two objects are equal according to `equals`, they must have the same `hashCode`.\n* If two objects have the same `hashCode`, they are not necessarily equal according to `equals`.\n\nIf you override `equals` but not `hashCode`, you may encounter issues when using your objects in collections, such as `HashMap` or `HashSet`. These collections use `hashCode` to store and retrieve objects, and if the `hashCode` is not properly implemented, it can lead to unexpected behavior.\n\n**Best Practices for Overriding `hashCode`**\n\nWhen overriding `hashCode`, follow these guidelines:\n\n* Use a prime number as the initial value (e.g., 17).\n* Multiply the current value by another prime number (e.g., 31) and add the hash code of each significant field.\n* Use the `Objects.hash` method or a similar utility method to simplify the implementation.\n\nHere is an example implementation of `hashCode` for a simple class:\n\n```java\npublic class Person {\n    private String name;\n    private int age;\n\n    @Override\n    public int hashCode() {\n        int result = 17; // initial prime number\n        result = 31 * result + name.hashCode(); // multiply by prime and add field hash code\n        result = 31 * result + age; // multiply by prime and add field hash code\n        return result;\n    }\n\n    @Override\n    public boolean equals(Object obj) {\n        if (this == obj) return true;\n        if (obj == null || getClass() != obj.getClass()) return false;\n        Person other = (Person) obj;\n        return name.equals(other.name) && age == other.age;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, you can use the `Objects.hash` method to simplify the implementation:\n\n```java\n@Override\npublic int hashCode() {\n    return Objects.hash(name, age);\n}\n```\n\nBy following these guidelines and best practices, you can ensure that your `hashCode` implementation is correct and efficient, and that it works correctly with your `equals` implementation.",
